WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.834 --> 00:00:02.801 align:start size:84% position:16%
Why are we so
fascinated with Mars?

00:00:02.801 --> 00:00:05.438 align:start size:88% position:13%
There's this visceral
connection that we have.

00:00:05.438 --> 00:00:07.673 align:start size:84% position:16%
It's been a constant
steady light

00:00:07.673 --> 00:00:09.675
in the night sky for us.

00:00:09.675 --> 00:00:13.713
You and I can go outside
tonight on a clear night,

00:00:13.713 --> 00:00:15.981
look towards the
southwestern sky,

00:00:15.981 --> 00:00:20.553
and see a bright orange
star, the Red Planet.

00:00:20.553 --> 00:00:23.389
(audience applauding)

00:00:23.389 --> 00:00:25.891 align:start size:84% position:16%
Looking at Mars,
it's also of interest

00:00:25.891 --> 00:00:30.430 line:0%
because it is within what
we call the Habitable Zone

00:00:30.430 --> 00:00:32.131
around the sun.

00:00:32.131 --> 00:00:34.166
And so we're going to
be exploring tonight

00:00:34.166 --> 00:00:35.401
a little bit more.

00:00:35.401 --> 00:00:38.571 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
I'd like to ask our
guests here, our experts

00:00:38.571 --> 00:00:40.273 line:0%
on a little bit about that.

00:00:40.273 --> 00:00:42.842
And let's get into
the challenges and
what it really takes

00:00:42.842 --> 00:00:44.376
to get to Mars.

00:00:44.376 --> 00:00:47.046
- Mars is incredibly
difficult to get onto,

00:00:47.046 --> 00:00:49.115
because you have to go
through the atmosphere.

00:00:49.115 --> 00:00:51.084 line:0%
And the atmosphere
is not your friend,

00:00:51.084 --> 00:00:53.352 line:0%
because it swells
up because of dust.

00:00:53.352 --> 00:00:55.388 line:0%
When there's a lot of
dust in the atmosphere,

00:00:55.388 --> 00:00:56.822 line:0%
it shrinks.

00:00:56.822 --> 00:00:59.458 align:start position:0%
There are lateral winds,
although the atmosphere is thin.

00:00:59.458 --> 00:01:03.195 align:start size:97% position:3%
But it is a scientific bonanza
once you're on the surface.

00:01:03.195 --> 00:01:07.466
It has ancient rivers
and ancient lakes,

00:01:07.466 --> 00:01:08.935
hydrothermal systems.

00:01:08.935 --> 00:01:11.303 align:start size:94% position:6%
All the evidence is there,
the geologic evidence.

00:01:11.303 --> 00:01:14.441 align:start size:84% position:16%
It's from the first
half of geologic time.

00:01:14.441 --> 00:01:17.676 align:start size:94% position:6%
So early in geologic time,
Mars was warm and wet,

00:01:17.676 --> 00:01:19.679
and the international
exploration of Mars

00:01:19.679 --> 00:01:23.316 align:start size:94% position:6%
robotically is all focused
on if it was habitable

00:01:23.316 --> 00:01:26.052
and whether or not life
got started and evolved

00:01:26.052 --> 00:01:27.620
and is still there.

00:01:27.620 --> 00:01:28.821
- That's amazing.

00:01:28.821 --> 00:01:32.092
So let's look at some
of the technology.

00:01:33.225 --> 00:01:35.361 align:start size:84% position:16%
Let's talk about
this character here.

00:01:35.361 --> 00:01:37.930 align:start size:94% position:6%
He's making a lot of
buzz in the media, right?

00:01:37.930 --> 00:01:41.667 align:start size:84% position:16%
Elon Musk, he's
the head of SpaceX,

00:01:41.667 --> 00:01:45.304 align:start size:97% position:3%
and his true love and
passion is space exploration.

00:01:45.304 --> 00:01:48.674
And his vision is to
send humans to Mars.

00:01:48.674 --> 00:01:51.110
So NASA isn't really alone.

00:01:51.110 --> 00:01:53.279
They have partnerships.

00:01:53.279 --> 00:01:54.513
Is that...
- Right.

00:01:54.513 --> 00:01:56.049 align:start size:88% position:13%
- [Andrew] Really going
to be integral now?

00:01:56.049 --> 00:01:58.384 line:0%
- Yes, so NASA historically
has partnered with people,

00:01:58.384 --> 00:02:01.354 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
has consulted and contracted
with organizations

00:02:01.354 --> 00:02:02.588 line:0%
all over the country.

00:02:02.588 --> 00:02:06.159
And so as we're looking
into this next phase,

00:02:06.159 --> 00:02:08.428
this going to Mars, there
are still going to have

00:02:08.428 --> 00:02:09.762
to be these partnerships.

00:02:09.762 --> 00:02:11.497
As you say, Elon Musk is one,

00:02:11.497 --> 00:02:13.899 align:start size:94% position:6%
but there are others
that are going to help us

00:02:13.899 --> 00:02:15.902 align:start size:84% position:16%
do the important
work of figuring out

00:02:15.902 --> 00:02:18.104
what, exactly, the
best technology is.

00:02:18.104 --> 00:02:19.204
But it is definitely
something that we're

00:02:19.204 --> 00:02:20.840
going to have to do together.

00:02:20.840 --> 00:02:21.907
- It's not an easy thing.

00:02:21.907 --> 00:02:22.841
- No.

00:02:22.841 --> 00:02:24.176
- Right, so take a look at this.

00:02:24.176 --> 00:02:26.679
- [Male] T-minus four minutes.

00:02:27.746 --> 00:02:30.817 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
- [Peter] We've reached
a tipping point.

00:02:30.817 --> 00:02:34.487 line:0%
Thousands of years from
now, whatever we become,

00:02:34.487 --> 00:02:37.824
whoever we are, we'll
look back at these

00:02:37.824 --> 00:02:40.426
next few decades as
the moment in time

00:02:40.426 --> 00:02:42.461 align:start size:81% position:19%
that we are moving
off this planet

00:02:42.461 --> 00:02:45.031
as a multi-planetary species.

00:02:45.031 --> 00:02:47.900
- [Male] BC and DC verify
F9 and Dragon R at startup.

00:02:47.900 --> 00:02:49.468
- [Male 2] F9 is in startup.

00:02:49.468 --> 00:02:52.571 line:0%
- And SpaceX stands
as nothing less than

00:02:52.571 --> 00:02:54.507 line:0%
a massive game changer.

00:02:55.941 --> 00:02:57.843 align:start size:97% position:3%
- [Male 3] Stage One, Stage
Two present for flight.

00:02:57.843 --> 00:02:59.812
- [Stephen] Elon Musk
says the only reason

00:02:59.812 --> 00:03:03.382
that I founded this company is
to get human beings to Mars.

00:03:03.382 --> 00:03:05.384
- [Male 4] LC, LD go for launch.

00:03:05.384 --> 00:03:08.654 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
- The key to making
Mars economical

00:03:08.654 --> 00:03:11.156 line:0%
is the reusability of rockets.

00:03:11.156 --> 00:03:12.725
- [Male5] T-minus one minute.

00:03:12.725 --> 00:03:14.193 align:start size:84% position:16%
- I just don't think
there's any way

00:03:14.193 --> 00:03:18.097 align:start size:97% position:3%
to have a self-sustaining Mars
space without reusability.

00:03:18.097 --> 00:03:21.667
Getting the cost down
is really fundamental.

00:03:21.667 --> 00:03:24.570 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
If wooden sailing ships in the
old days were not reusable,

00:03:24.570 --> 00:03:26.438 align:start size:88% position:13% line:0%
I don't think the United
States would exist.

00:03:26.438 --> 00:03:27.707
- [Male 5] T-minus 30 seconds.

00:03:27.707 --> 00:03:31.410
- And if they nail this
ability to land a rocket

00:03:31.410 --> 00:03:34.313 align:start size:94% position:6%
any way they want on
Earth, then they can nail

00:03:34.313 --> 00:03:35.715
doing it on Mars.

00:03:35.715 --> 00:03:37.382
- [Male 5] T-minus 15.

00:03:37.382 --> 00:03:38.818
- This flight is a huge deal.

00:03:38.818 --> 00:03:41.420 align:start size:81% position:19% line:0%
We haven't yet
landed the rocket.

00:03:41.420 --> 00:03:43.589 align:start size:84% position:16% line:0%
So this is going to
be hopefully our first

00:03:43.589 --> 00:03:45.157 line:0%
successful landing.

00:03:45.157 --> 00:03:49.628 align:start size:84% position:16%
- [Male 5] T-minus
10, nine, eight, seven

00:03:49.628 --> 00:03:53.800
six, five, four, three,

00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:56.569
two, one, zero.

00:03:58.237 --> 00:04:00.472
We have liftoff of Falcon 9.

00:04:00.472 --> 00:04:05.078 align:start size:84% position:16%
(spectators cheering
and applauding)

00:04:05.078 --> 00:04:07.814
(dramatic music)

00:04:20.592 --> 00:04:23.195
- [Male 6] Vehicle's reached
maximum aerodynamic pressure.

00:04:23.195 --> 00:04:26.065 align:start size:97% position:3%
- [Male 7] Stage 1
propulsion is still nominal.

00:04:26.065 --> 00:04:27.767
Altitude 32 kilometers.

00:04:27.767 --> 00:04:29.569 align:start size:84% position:16%
Speed at one
kilometer per second.

00:04:29.569 --> 00:04:32.338 align:start size:81% position:19%
Downrange distance
13 kilometers.

00:04:33.505 --> 00:04:36.275
(explosive sounds)

00:04:36.275 --> 00:04:39.445
(slow dramatic music)

00:05:02.434 --> 00:05:04.770 size:88% position:44%
- [Casey] Space is defined
by the strange relationship

00:05:04.770 --> 00:05:08.474 align:start size:84% position:16%
between failure,
risk and innovation,

00:05:08.474 --> 00:05:10.610
which is you can take risks.

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:13.979 align:start size:84% position:16%
You can try something
very innovative.

00:05:13.979 --> 00:05:16.616
But you're more likely to fail.

00:05:16.616 --> 00:05:20.153 align:start size:84% position:16%
- So what was it
supposed to look like?

00:05:20.153 --> 00:05:22.821 align:start size:84% position:16%
Well, you'd have the
booster going up,

00:05:22.821 --> 00:05:25.090
and what I'm showing
you here is going to be

00:05:25.090 --> 00:05:28.428
a composite, a long
exposure photograph.

00:05:29.595 --> 00:05:31.097
What it's supposed
to have looked like,

00:05:31.097 --> 00:05:32.899 align:start size:84% position:16%
and then the booster
coming back down.

00:05:32.899 --> 00:05:35.735 align:start size:97% position:3%
And what you see on your
right hand side of the screen

00:05:35.735 --> 00:05:40.138 align:start size:97% position:3%
is the booster that came
down back onto the launchpad.

00:05:40.138 --> 00:05:44.743 align:start size:88% position:13%
And what I want to know,
Jedidah, is why is it

00:05:44.743 --> 00:05:48.781
so important to
have reusability?

00:05:48.781 --> 00:05:51.651 align:start size:84% position:16%
I'm talking about
Mars, going to Mars.

00:05:51.651 --> 00:05:52.918
Why is that so important?

00:05:52.918 --> 00:05:55.755
- Yeah, over the long
term, the hope is that

00:05:55.755 --> 00:05:58.724 align:start size:97% position:3%
if you can reuse something,
it's cheaper, right?

00:05:58.724 --> 00:06:00.759 align:start size:94% position:6%
You want it to be cheaper
and more efficient.

00:06:00.759 --> 00:06:04.363 align:start size:97% position:3%
It's sort of your workhorse
that you just continue to use.

00:06:04.363 --> 00:06:06.932
It's not always the case
that things are cheaper

00:06:06.932 --> 00:06:09.768
when you reuse them,
but you want something

00:06:09.768 --> 00:06:13.406 align:start size:84% position:16%
that you can use,
rinse, recycle, reuse.

00:06:13.406 --> 00:06:15.040
That's rinse, repeat,
that's what you want.

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:18.477 align:start size:97% position:3%
The other thing is, you
want to be able to use that

00:06:18.477 --> 00:06:21.914 align:start size:84% position:16%
piece of technology
as scaffolding for the

00:06:21.914 --> 00:06:23.148
next thing you do.

00:06:23.148 --> 00:06:25.718 align:start size:88% position:13%
Maybe you use a piece
of your booster to build

00:06:25.718 --> 00:06:26.986
the first structure, right?

00:06:26.986 --> 00:06:29.322
Maybe you recycle
it in that way.

00:06:29.322 --> 00:06:32.257
So you hope, first, that
there's a cost savings.

00:06:32.257 --> 00:06:33.859
You hope that there's
a sort of efficiency

00:06:33.859 --> 00:06:35.328
that you can build in.

00:06:35.328 --> 00:06:37.730
And third, that you can
use it as a scaffolding

00:06:37.730 --> 00:06:39.064
for the next thing.

00:06:39.064 --> 00:06:42.334
- Let's look at the
idea of the timeline.

00:06:42.334 --> 00:06:44.770 align:start size:97% position:3% line:0%
What is it, like seven
months to get there, right?

00:06:44.770 --> 00:06:46.338 line:0%
Just to get there.

00:06:46.338 --> 00:06:51.243 line:0%
So we need to, right now,
start building up on that,

00:06:51.243 --> 00:06:54.280 align:start size:88% position:13%
and one of the most
recent attempts at that

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:58.684
is the year-long mission that
both the U.S. and the Russians

00:06:58.684 --> 00:07:00.152
took part in.

00:07:00.152 --> 00:07:03.922 align:start position:0%
U.S. astronaut Scott Kelly,
you can see here in this image,

00:07:03.922 --> 00:07:07.159
spent a whole year,
coming back in March,

00:07:07.159 --> 00:07:10.229
exploring this whole
concept of what happens

00:07:10.229 --> 00:07:12.064
to human body

00:07:13.365 --> 00:07:16.835 align:start size:97% position:3%
being exposed to microgravity
for long durations?

00:07:16.835 --> 00:07:20.739
So we're starting to
work on those aspects.

00:07:20.739 --> 00:07:23.942 align:start size:84% position:16%
And I'd like to know,
I mean, what toll

00:07:23.942 --> 00:07:25.544
does it take on the human body?

00:07:25.544 --> 00:07:27.713
What does space travel,
long term space travel,

00:07:27.713 --> 00:07:29.648
do to a human body?

00:07:29.648 --> 00:07:31.983 align:start size:88% position:13%
- The truth is we don't
really know, right?

00:07:31.983 --> 00:07:33.819
We've never done this before.

00:07:33.819 --> 00:07:35.221
Commander Scott Kelly
and his colleagues

00:07:35.221 --> 00:07:37.323 align:start size:84% position:16%
were sort of the
first to stay in space

00:07:37.323 --> 00:07:38.557
as long as they did.

00:07:38.557 --> 00:07:42.160 align:start size:88% position:13%
And even there, they had
a lot more protection

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:44.896
from Earth, from the
sort of microgravity.

00:07:44.896 --> 00:07:46.532
Also, we were still
in the magnetosphere,

00:07:46.532 --> 00:07:48.267 align:start size:84% position:16%
so they had protection
from radiation.

00:07:48.267 --> 00:07:49.468 align:start size:84% position:16%
Still, more radiation
than they'd have

00:07:49.468 --> 00:07:50.669
if they were where we are,

00:07:50.669 --> 00:07:52.270 align:start size:84% position:16%
but we don't know
what's going to happen

00:07:52.270 --> 00:07:55.207 align:start size:88% position:13%
when you put a person
in sort of interstellar,

00:07:55.207 --> 00:07:58.544 align:start size:84% position:16%
interplanetary travel
for seven months.

00:07:58.544 --> 00:07:59.812
We don't know.

00:07:59.812 --> 00:08:01.781
We know already that
you lose bone mass.

00:08:01.781 --> 00:08:03.883
We know that you've got
these radiation effects.

00:08:03.883 --> 00:08:05.984 align:start size:94% position:6%
We have no idea about
the psychological impact.

00:08:05.984 --> 00:08:07.519 align:start size:88% position:13%
So these are all
things that we're still

00:08:07.519 --> 00:08:10.122
trying to understand, and
his mission, their mission

00:08:10.122 --> 00:08:13.526 align:start size:97% position:3%
is critical to understanding
at least step one

00:08:13.526 --> 00:08:14.760
in the process.

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:18.297
So there's a lot
to be understood.

00:08:18.297 --> 00:08:21.033 align:start size:84% position:16%
- When we get there,
I'd like to know

00:08:21.033 --> 00:08:23.335 align:start size:94% position:6%
how are we going to
choose the landing sites?

00:08:23.335 --> 00:08:26.538 align:start size:97% position:3%
Now, what I've got here
for you is the map of Mars,

00:08:26.538 --> 00:08:30.142 align:start size:97% position:3%
and these are potential
landing sites that we have.

00:08:30.142 --> 00:08:32.678
What goes in, Ray, maybe
you can speak to this,

00:08:32.678 --> 00:08:33.913
about choosing...

00:08:33.913 --> 00:08:35.414 align:start size:84% position:16%
- Well, there are
engineering aspects.

00:08:35.414 --> 00:08:36.548
There are science aspects.

00:08:36.548 --> 00:08:37.716
You want to go to a place that's

00:08:37.716 --> 00:08:40.019
scientifically interesting.

00:08:40.019 --> 00:08:42.321 align:start size:88% position:13%
Could be layer
deposits that represent

00:08:42.321 --> 00:08:44.456 align:start size:84% position:16%
kind of ancient
riverbeds or lakes.

00:08:44.456 --> 00:08:48.293 align:start position:0%
It could be ancient hydrothermal
deposits from volcanoes,

00:08:48.293 --> 00:08:50.162
or whatever it turns out to be.

00:08:50.162 --> 00:08:51.930
But you also need
to land in a place

00:08:51.930 --> 00:08:53.698
that you can get back out of.

00:08:53.698 --> 00:08:55.367
And that's the plus or minus 50.

00:08:55.367 --> 00:08:57.436
It's relatively easy
to go back into orbit.

00:08:57.436 --> 00:08:58.904
And not too cold,

00:08:58.904 --> 00:09:00.572 align:start size:84% position:16%
because Mars is
cold to begin with.

00:09:00.572 --> 00:09:03.241 align:start size:84% position:16%
It's way below
freezing on average.

00:09:03.241 --> 00:09:04.810
And if you go to
the high latitudes,

00:09:04.810 --> 00:09:06.178
it's super cold.

00:09:06.178 --> 00:09:08.747
- You know, the ultimate
goal is to send humans.

00:09:08.747 --> 00:09:12.818
So what I'd like to know
is what do you guys think

00:09:12.818 --> 00:09:14.554
in terms of the specialties?

00:09:14.554 --> 00:09:18.157 align:start size:94% position:6%
What kind of people should
we be sending to Mars?

00:09:18.157 --> 00:09:20.058 align:start size:88% position:13%
- It's an important
point to recognize that

00:09:20.058 --> 00:09:22.995
going to Mars is going
to be what they call

00:09:22.995 --> 00:09:24.630
sociotechnological.

00:09:24.630 --> 00:09:26.499
It is not just going
to be the technical

00:09:26.499 --> 00:09:27.732
that takes us there.

00:09:27.732 --> 00:09:28.901 align:start size:84% position:16%
It's not just going
to be the sociological

00:09:28.901 --> 00:09:30.269
or the psychological.

00:09:30.269 --> 00:09:33.005 align:start position:0%
It is going to be the
interaction of those two things,

00:09:33.005 --> 00:09:35.174
the optimization of
those two things,

00:09:35.174 --> 00:09:36.342
that makes it happen.

00:09:36.342 --> 00:09:38.511 align:start size:88% position:13%
So, yeah, you want
people that have skills

00:09:38.511 --> 00:09:39.744
that are technical.

00:09:39.744 --> 00:09:42.214 align:start size:84% position:16%
You want them to be
able to fix things and

00:09:42.214 --> 00:09:43.515
create experiments.

00:09:43.515 --> 00:09:45.317
Physicians, you need
someone there in case

00:09:45.317 --> 00:09:46.585
you have medical emergencies.

00:09:46.585 --> 00:09:50.055
But you also want the
kind of mental stamina

00:09:50.055 --> 00:09:51.957
to be able to deal with
all of the conditions

00:09:51.957 --> 00:09:54.960
that you're going to
be sort of faced with.

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:59.331
So as I look at it, I think
about not just your skills

00:09:59.331 --> 00:10:01.733
in terms of what you've
been educated to do,

00:10:01.733 --> 00:10:04.203 align:start size:84% position:16%
I think of a variety
of perspectives,

00:10:04.203 --> 00:10:07.640
of life experiences,
of outlooks on life,

00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:10.142
because all of those things
are going to be necessary

00:10:10.142 --> 00:10:11.343
to make this work.

00:10:11.343 --> 00:10:13.745 align:start size:84% position:16%
So we need an
inclusive environment

00:10:13.745 --> 00:10:16.682
and an inclusive set of people.

00:10:16.682 --> 00:10:18.950 align:start size:97% position:3%
- [Andrew] I guess growing
food is going to be important,

00:10:18.950 --> 00:10:20.419
isn't it, Jedidah?

00:10:20.419 --> 00:10:22.988
- Yeah, so it's this idea
of being able to reuse

00:10:22.988 --> 00:10:25.457 align:start size:88% position:13%
and create a sense of
self-sufficiency, right?

