00:15:02.033 --> 00:15:04.703
- Okay. Why?

00:15:04.703 --> 00:15:05.971
- It's out of equilibrium.

00:15:05.971 --> 00:15:08.506
I mean, Mars is cold and
dry today for a reason.

00:15:08.506 --> 00:15:11.010
Early in geologic time,
there were volcanoes.

00:15:11.010 --> 00:15:13.278 align:start size:94% position:6%
There was a massive amount
of greenhouse warming

00:15:13.278 --> 00:15:14.679
from the gases coming up.

00:15:14.679 --> 00:15:17.115 align:start size:94% position:6%
Because it's small a
planet relative to Earth,

00:15:17.115 --> 00:15:21.319 align:start position:0%
it stopped its internal
activity sooner than the Earth.

00:15:21.319 --> 00:15:24.823 align:start size:97% position:3%
So the gases in the atmosphere
were on a one-way trip

00:15:24.823 --> 00:15:27.859
to be oxidized and
placed into minerals.

00:15:27.859 --> 00:15:30.663 align:start size:97% position:3%
So if you increase the amount
of sunlight with mirrors,

00:15:30.663 --> 00:15:33.464 align:start position:0%
or whatever, you can
sublimate, get more water vapor

00:15:33.464 --> 00:15:35.267
in the atmosphere, more rain.

00:15:35.267 --> 00:15:36.435
But what's going to happen?

00:15:36.435 --> 00:15:37.970 align:start size:84% position:16%
It's going to react
with the rocks

00:15:37.970 --> 00:15:41.840
and go back down into the
subsurface eventually.

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:44.643 align:start size:94% position:6%
There's a famous reaction
that was codified

00:15:44.643 --> 00:15:46.145
by Harold Urey.

00:15:46.145 --> 00:15:50.582 align:start size:97% position:3%
He's a very distinguished
Nobel Prize winning chemist.

00:15:50.582 --> 00:15:53.385 align:start size:88% position:13%
And it's the way the
Earth stays more or less

00:15:53.385 --> 00:15:54.819
the way we like it.

00:15:54.819 --> 00:15:56.288
Sometimes it goes
into deep freeze.

00:15:56.288 --> 00:15:58.056
Sometimes it's really warm.

00:15:58.056 --> 00:16:01.359
But what happens is, is the
volcanoes pump up the gases

00:16:01.359 --> 00:16:02.627
that keep us warm.

00:16:02.627 --> 00:16:05.464 align:start size:88% position:13%
But the hydrologic cycle
consumes those gases,

00:16:05.464 --> 00:16:08.333 align:start size:88% position:13%
as carbonic acids,
CO2 goes into the water,

00:16:08.333 --> 00:16:10.669
and it reacts and
forms limestones.

00:16:10.669 --> 00:16:12.704
But the limestones
go back downstairs,

00:16:12.704 --> 00:16:15.607 align:start size:84% position:16%
get decomposed, and
the gases come back up

00:16:15.607 --> 00:16:18.576
as greenhouse gases
through volcanoes.

00:16:18.576 --> 00:16:21.279
If you stop the internal engine,

00:16:21.279 --> 00:16:23.448 align:start size:84% position:16%
you go in the
one-way deep freeze.

00:16:23.448 --> 00:16:24.716
It's what happened to Mars,

00:16:24.716 --> 00:16:26.618 align:start size:84% position:16%
because it's smaller
than the Earth.

00:16:26.618 --> 00:16:28.653 align:start size:88% position:13%
So terraforming can
increase the temperature

00:16:28.653 --> 00:16:31.356
of the surface, but you
can get some gas out.

00:16:31.356 --> 00:16:32.925 align:start size:84% position:16%
But it will eventually
get corroded

00:16:32.925 --> 00:16:35.260
and put back down
into the subsurface

00:16:35.260 --> 00:16:36.761
in a one-way trip.

00:16:36.761 --> 00:16:39.564
So it may work for
a couple decades,

00:16:39.564 --> 00:16:42.768
but over longer
time, it's bogus,

00:16:42.768 --> 00:16:43.936
in my opinion.

00:16:45.304 --> 00:16:48.473 align:start size:94% position:6%
- And also would decimate
whatever is there

00:16:48.473 --> 00:16:50.208
that we don't know yet.

00:16:50.208 --> 00:16:53.979 align:start size:84% position:16%
- Yeah, there's a very
